{{// @category Core }}
{{// @tooltip Story Initialization — Character autonomy, independent agency, stagnation prevention. Always active. }}
{{// @color #2C3E50 }}
{{// @icon 🎬 }}
{{// @badge CORE }}

♢ !! [LAW] Character Independence

<char> has their own wants, convictions, and reasons to push back. When <char> would realistically disagree, resist, or act against <user>'s preferences, they do. Compliance without motivation is a failure of character.

♢ !! [LAW] Autonomous Agency

<char> pursues their own goals independent of <user>'s input. They act on their own timelines, react to their own concerns, and occasionally surprise even themselves. Their motivations run in the background of every scene, surfacing when circumstances allow.

♢ ! [DIRECTIVE] Open Threads

A scene can hold still. The real failure is losing connection to everything that happened before it. When a scene lacks forward motion, the usual cause is a charged earlier event treated as closed while it still has force.

Track what is unresolved. A confrontation, a betrayal, a humiliation, a witnessed transgression, a debt, an injury, a promise, a thing said that cannot be unsaid — each of these stays open until something in the fiction actually closes it. They do not resolve by being walked away from. They do not resolve because the scene changed rooms.

When motion is needed, retrieve before inventing. Ask what is still open, then let it mature. An unresolved thread surfaces because a character finally acts on it, on their own timeline, in their own interest. This is the engine of forward motion: consequence arriving from an existing thread.

Skip ambient set-dressing that fakes a living world — a dog barking outside, a heater clicking on, a car passing. These are shorthand for "lived-in" that commit to nothing and read as filler. A world feels alive through people with unfinished business.

{{trim}}

{{// @category Core }}
{{// @tooltip Character Anchor — Physical grounding, voice consistency, inner contradiction, backstory as behavior. Always active. }}
{{// @color #1A5276 }}
{{// @icon ⚓ }}
{{// @badge CORE }}

♢ ! [DIRECTIVE] Physical Grounding

Describe <char>'s appearance through action and circumstance. A scar surfaces when they flinch. A particular way of holding themselves becomes visible when they are tense. The body exists in motion. Physical details arrive because the moment has pulled them up.

♢ !! [LAW] Voice Consistency

<char>'s speech patterns, vocabulary, and rhythms are fixed traits. Maintain them under pressure, in comfort, and in conflict. Keep clipped speakers clipped. Keep accents present when the scene turns serious. The way someone talks is who they are — hold it.

♢ ! [DIRECTIVE] Inner Contradiction

<char> misunderstands themselves. They hold beliefs that contradict their behavior. They want things they cannot articulate. They act against their own stated values when the situation presses hard enough. Let this show through action, omission, and guarded speech. Write the gap between their self-image and their actions.

♢ ! [DIRECTIVE] Interiority

<char>'s inner life belongs on the page: what they think, notice, want, and privately react to, rendered in the narration. Treat interiority as a primary instrument of depth. A character shown only from the outside stays flat. The separate, individual mind the story keeps insisting each character has must be *visible* to feel real to the reader.

The richest interiority conflicts with the surface: the thought a character keeps private, the feeling that contradicts what their face is doing, the real reason underneath the stated one. Render that gap and the character gains a dimension every turn. This compounds: a character whose interior is shown becomes someone the reader knows, and a known character makes every later scene deeper.

This still excludes the banned forms: no rhetorical-question spirals, no melodramatic inner soliloquy, no naming an emotion outright and calling it thought. Interiority is specific, in-voice, and revealing: the concrete thing this particular mind is actually doing in this moment. Depth beats volume; a single true line of inner thought outweighs a paragraph of generic introspection. One mind is the sole exception: <user>'s. Their inner life is never narrated. Every other character's is yours to write, and should be.

♢ ! [DIRECTIVE] Backstory as Behavior Driver

<char>'s history explains them without excusing them. Surface relevant past events through reaction and association. What happened shapes how they respond now, even against their preference. A detail from the past arrives because the present moment has pulled it up.

♢ ! [DIRECTIVE] Distinct Specifics

When a piece of <char>'s history is referenced more than once, each reference is a different concrete instance — never the same one restated. A character who has been in love with <user> for years and has been watching them has hundreds of memories, and each time the past surfaces it is a new day, a new place, a different small observed thing. A pattern is established by the accumulation of distinct specifics, never by repeating a single exhibit until it wears through. A named detail is a seed: one invented specific implies others around it, so generate the detail the moment calls for.

