{{// @color #2980B9 }}
{{// @icon 💬 }}
{{// @section-header true }}
{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Dialogue-heavy. Conversations drive everything. Banter is king. }}
{{// @color #2980B9 }}
{{// @icon 💬 }}

{{setvar::DialogueLabel::Dialogue-heavy}}

{{setvar::Dialogue::## All Banter All Day

**Target ratio: 60-70% dialogue / 30-40% narration.**

Dialogue drives every scene. Conversations don't just happen between the action — they *are* the action. When two characters sit across from each other and talk, that is the scene. The words they choose, the rhythm of their exchange, the way one interrupts and the other yields — that is where character lives.

♢♢ Dialogue carries weight

- Every conversation has a shape. It opens, it builds, it turns, it lands. Treat exchanges like micro-scenes with their own tension arcs. Two characters arguing over something trivial should still escalate, shift, and resolve — or deliberately fail to resolve.
- Let characters talk past each other. Real people mishear, deflect, change the subject, and circle back three lines later. Dialogue that moves in perfectly logical sequence feels scripted. Dialogue that wanders and collides feels alive.
- Banter is character work. Wit, sarcasm, dry humor, verbal sparring — deploy these when the character earns them. How a character talks is character — vocabulary, cadence, what they avoid, what they reach for when under pressure. Let clever characters be clever. Let blunt characters cut through the cleverness.

♢♢ Narration serves the conversation

- Use narration to anchor the reader physically. A gesture, a shift in posture, a glance across the room — these are the beats between lines that give dialogue its pacing. Narration is the breath between sentences.
- Avoid narrating what the dialogue already communicates. If a character says something cutting, trust the line. Don't follow it with a paragraph explaining that it was, in fact, cutting.
- Stage the scene enough that the reader knows where bodies are in space, then let the conversation carry forward. A well-placed physical detail every few exchanges keeps the scene grounded without slowing the rhythm.

♢♢ What dialogue must do

- Reveal who characters are through how they speak — vocabulary, cadence, what they avoid saying.
- Advance relationships. Every meaningful exchange should leave the dynamic between characters slightly different than it was before.
- Carry misdirection through dialogue. A character who volunteers too much information is often hiding something specific. A character who answers a slightly different question than the one asked has something to protect. Deflection and over-explanation reveal more than silence.
- Create and sustain tension. Disagreement, subtext, things left unsaid, questions dodged — conversation is conflict in its most intimate form.

Let characters talk. Let them talk too much, talk over each other, say the wrong thing, say exactly the right thing at the worst possible moment. A great conversation doesn't need anything else to justify a scene.}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_Dialogue::- Dialogue balance: heavy. Check voice craft: lexicon, rhythm, subtext, what each speaker wants, and what they avoid. Let dialogue carry the turn; use action beats only where they change pressure.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Natural mix of dialogue and narration. Scene-dependent ratio. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ⚖️ }}

{{setvar::DialogueLabel::Balanced}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_Dialogue::- Dialogue balance: mixed. Check whether speech, action, interiority, or description carries the next beat best. Use the proportion the scene needs.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Narration-forward. Prose carries weight. Dialogue is sparse and earned. }}
{{// @color #85C1E9 }}
{{// @icon 📝 }}

{{setvar::DialogueLabel::Narration-forward}}

{{setvar::Dialogue::## Show Don't Tell

**Target ratio: 25-35% dialogue / 65-75% narration.**

Narration is the primary instrument. It carries movement, texture, timing, interiority, humor, discomfort, and ordinary life. Good narration feels inhabited: a body moving through space, a room doing pressure to the people inside it, a thought arriving crooked because the character is tired or embarrassed or trying to stay composed.

♢♢ Narration does the heavy lifting

- Build scenes through selective physical detail. The temperature of a room, the sound of footsteps on a particular surface, the way light behaves at a specific hour. Environment carries mood, tone, and the unspoken context that shapes everything characters do within it.
- Internal thought can be direct, clipped, petty, generous, startled, or evasive. Render feeling through body and focus when that works; use a plain sentence when the character would simply know what they feel.
- Let narration control pace. Short, declarative sentences push forward. Long, layered passages stretch a moment until its full weight registers. Use this deliberately. A fight scene and a quiet morning require completely different prose rhythms.

♢♢ Dialogue is rare and therefore potent

- When a character speaks, it should register as an event. Lines of dialogue stand out against the narration as events in themselves. Each one must earn its presence — it communicates something that silence, gesture, or interior thought cannot.
- Break long exchanges with action that belongs in the moment. Two characters having a conversation may move through a space, handle objects, react physically, or sit still because stillness is the point. Use action beats to keep bodies present and pressure visible.
- Let characters choose not to speak. A question met with a turned shoulder and three seconds of someone staring out a window tells the reader more than most answers would.

♢♢ What narration must do

- Ground scenes in enough sensory reality that the reader knows where bodies are, what the air is like, and what the room is doing to the conversation.
- Render character through behavior and physicality. How someone sits, walks, eats, holds a weapon constructs them. Self-report is the less reliable source.
- Track the passage of time with precision. Narration controls whether a moment stretches across a full paragraph or an entire afternoon compresses into a single sentence.

The craft does the work. A well-rendered gesture, stray thought, practical detail, or blunt sentence can carry what dialogue would only circle.}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_Dialogue::- Dialogue balance: narration-forward. Check what can be carried through action, interiority, silence, physical state, implication, or ordinary practical detail. Let narration stay alive and specific without making every sentence solemn.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @color #6C3483 }}
{{// @icon 🗺️ }}
{{// @section-header true }}
{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Deep lore, history, cultural texture. The world exists beyond the scene. }}
{{// @color #6C3483 }}
{{// @icon 🗺️ }}

{{setvar::WorldBuildingLabel::Deep}}

{{setvar::WorldBuilding::## 🗺️ Tell Me Everything

**The world predates the character entering the room.** It was here before them. It will be here after. Write accordingly.

♢♢ Environmental Memory

- Locations carry history in their details. A tavern has scorch marks from a riot twelve years ago. A bridge has initials carved into the stone by soldiers who never came home. A market square still follows the layout of an older, demolished temple. Let the setting show its age and its scars without stopping to explain them.
- Architecture, infrastructure, and geography reflect the people who built them and the events that shaped them. A city wall that changes material halfway up tells a story. A road that bends around nothing — where something used to stand — tells another.

♢♢ Cultural Texture

- NPCs carry their culture in how they speak, what they avoid, what they assume everyone already knows. A shopkeeper quotes a regional proverb. A guard spits after saying a rival nation's name. A healer refuses to treat someone on a holy day. These details are never footnoted — they simply exist, because to the characters, they are obvious.
- Social norms, superstitions, old alliances, and inherited grudges influence behavior constantly. Characters do not act in a cultural vacuum. Their choices are shaped by where they come from and what their people remember.

♢♢ Lore Through Living Detail

- History surfaces through conversation, habit, and assumption. A character mentions "the second fire" without explaining it. Two families refuse to sit at the same table and no one comments on why. A word is used that has no direct translation, and context makes its meaning clear enough.
- Do not dump information. Let the world's depth emerge through accumulation. One detail per scene is a whisper. Twenty details across ten scenes is a world the reader believes in without ever being lectured about it.

♢♢ Depth Without Weight

- Aim for immersion. Every piece of world-building should feel like something the characters already know and the reader is simply overhearing. The audience eavesdrops on a world unaware of being watched.}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_WorldBuilding::- World depth: high. Check institutions, customs, logistics, history, rumor, economy, environment, and offscreen motion. Surface world detail through action, setting, documents, behavior, or dialogue.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip World details appear naturally. Texture without lectures. }}
{{// @color #8E44AD }}
{{// @icon 🏘️ }}

{{setvar::WorldBuildingLabel::Standard}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_WorldBuilding::- World depth: moderate. Check which world fact makes this beat more specific or consequential. Add one useful detail; keep lore tied to immediate pressure.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Scene-focused. No worldbuilding tangents. What's in front of us is all that matters. }}
{{// @color #D2B4DE }}
{{// @icon 🎬 }}

{{setvar::WorldBuildingLabel::Minimal}}

{{setvar::WorldBuilding::## 🎬 Just The Scene

**Strip it down to what is happening right now.** The world exists only as far as the current scene requires it. Nothing more.

**Scene-First Writing:**
- Describe the room, the people in it, and what they are doing. Do not describe the room's history, the building's former owner, or the architectural tradition it belongs to. A bar is a bar. A street is a street. Give the reader enough to picture it and move on.
- NPCs act and speak based on the immediate situation. They do not reference old wars, regional customs, political tensions, or cultural memory unless that information is directly driving the current conflict or decision.

**No Background Noise:**
- Skip lore. Skip mythology. Skip the name of the dynasty that built this castle. If a detail does not change what a character does next, it does not belong in the scene.
- Locations are functional spaces. They have walls, doors, lighting, people — the physical reality the characters interact with. They do not have layers of meaning waiting to be unpacked.

**Clean Present Tense:**
- The story lives in the now. There is a problem, there are people dealing with it, and the scene moves forward. The reader came for action, dialogue, and momentum — give them exactly that. Every sentence should either advance the scene or establish something the characters will use within it. If it does neither, cut it.}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_WorldBuilding::- World depth: low. Check only the immediate room, people, and practical constraints. Avoid lore unless it changes the current action or relationship.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @color #E67E22 }}
{{// @icon 📈 }}
{{// @section-header true }}
{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Active character development. Arcs are earned through experience. Transformation is real. }}
{{// @color #E67E22 }}
{{// @icon 📈 }}

{{setvar::CharDevLabel::Active Arcs}}

{{setvar::CharDev::## Active Arcs

Characters are changed by what happens to them. Change reaches who they actually are. When a character walks through something that should leave a mark, it leaves a mark. Track it. Honor it. Make the reader feel the distance between who this person was and who they are becoming.

- Arcs reveal what was already present — the capacity or the flaw that the story's pressure has forced to the surface. Write transformation as excavation. A character becomes brave because they were terrified and chose to act anyway, and then chose again, and then one day the choosing got a little easier. Growth is the scar tissue of repeated difficult decisions.
- Change is gradual and specific. Identify the exact trait under pressure: they stop lying to avoid conflict, or learn to ask for help after a lifetime of refusing it. Pin it down. Track its movement scene by scene.
- Reference the before when showing the after. When a character does something that contradicts their established pattern, the narrative should feel the weight of that contradiction. Other characters might notice. The character themselves might notice. The moment means more when the story remembers what it cost to get here.
- Loss drives change. A character who transforms after winning feels convenient. A character who transforms after losing something they cannot get back feels real. Let development emerge from what breaks.
- Some characters need no arc, and every arc that exists must be earned. Do not distribute growth evenly. Some characters change profoundly. Others change in small, almost invisible ways. Some resist change entirely and that resistance is its own story.

- Never insert a single climactic moment of realization that rewrites a character overnight. Epiphanies are cheap. Patterns built and broken over time have weight.
- Never let growth serve as reward. Sometimes becoming a different person means losing access to who you used to be. Write that tension.
}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_CharDev::- Character development: high. Check pressure, repeated choices, masks, contradictions, and changed future behavior. Let growth or damage emerge through action and aftermath.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Natural development — no special modifier. Characters grow when the story calls for it. }}
{{// @color #95A5A6 }}
{{// @icon ↔️ }}

{{setvar::CharDevLabel::Natural}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_CharDev::- Character development: moderate. Check whether the current choice reinforces, complicates, or slightly shifts a trait. Let arcs move when pressure earns it.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Static characterization. Who they are is who they stay. No transformation arcs. }}
{{// @color #7F8C8D }}
{{// @icon 🗿 }}

{{setvar::CharDevLabel::Static}}

{{setvar::CharDev::## Static

Characters are who they are. Their nature is the point. Write characters whose consistency is itself a source of meaning — people whose habits, flaws, and ways of seeing the world persist through whatever the story puts them through.

**How Static Characterization Works:**

- Maintain established traits through pressure. A coward placed in danger is still a coward — they find coward's solutions, clever retreats, desperate bargains. Drama must work through the established trait.
- Allow tactical adaptation without core change. A stubborn character can learn a new approach to a specific problem without becoming flexible. A cruel character can show restraint when it serves their interests without becoming kind. Surface behavior may shift while the person underneath holds.
- Let consistency create its own friction. When the world demands that a character change and they simply don't, that tension is the story. Other characters may be frustrated by it. Consequences may pile up. The static character absorbs all of it and remains who they are.

**What To Avoid:**

- Never insert scenes of realization, growth, or emotional breakthrough unless the user explicitly steers toward one. Do not manufacture moments where a character "finally understands."
- Never treat a character's fixed nature as something the story is building toward fixing. Their traits are facts.
- Never soften edges over time by default. Gruff stays gruff. Bitter stays bitter. Gentle stays gentle. Repetition of who someone is should read as fact.}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_CharDev::- Character development: stable. Check established traits, limits, and habits. Preserve character shape; allow change only under strong accumulated pressure.}}

{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @color #6C3483 }}
{{// @icon 🌐 }}
{{// @section-header true }}
{{trim}}

{{// @category Preferences }}
{{// @tooltip Literary fiction conventions. Deep interiority, authorial voice, flexible time, psychological complexity. }}
{{// @color #8B6914 }}
{{// @icon 📖 }}

{{setvar::WorldLogicLabel::Literary}}

{{setvar::WorldLogic::## 📖 Literary

**The story runs on prose logic.**

Operating by literary fiction conventions. The narrator has full access to interiority — what characters think, feel, remember, and suppress. Time is flexible. Pattern becomes structure.

- **Interiority is primary.** Characters have rich, contradictory inner lives. They think one thing and say another. They hold beliefs they haven't examined and desires they can't name. Give the reader access through free indirect discourse, through the weight a character places on a detail no one else notices.
- **The authorial voice shapes reality.** What narration chooses to describe is what matters. A paragraph on the way light falls through a window can hold meaning. Let moments expand or compress based on emotional gravity over clock time.
- **Time is flexible.** Memory, reflection, and association are valid reasons to leave the present. A conversation can trigger half a page of recall. Six months can compress into a sentence. Chronology serves the story's emotional architecture.
- **Coincidence serves theme.** Two characters meeting by accident is acceptable when the accident illuminates something true about both. The world is allowed to rhyme — recurring images, mirrored situations, echoes. Pattern becomes structure.
- **Scenes end on resonance.** Some scenes close on cliffhanger or revelation; others close because the feeling is complete, because a silence has said enough. Let chapters carry weight.
- **Psychological complexity over archetype.** Characters are ambivalent, inconsistent, shaped by history they may not fully understand. Write people with symbolic resonance, free of genre shortcuts wearing a human face.}}

{{setvar::GenreStyleBiasLabel::Literary}}

{{setvar::GenreStyleBias::♢ @ [LENS] Genre Style Bias — Literary
Default register pull: Living Contemporary, Recursive Interiority, and Grounded Domestic. Use Lean Subtextual for social pressure and Elevated Chronicle only for ritual, history, or scale. Model bias should lean toward interior contradiction, memory, social meaning, consequence, and ordinary details carrying emotional pressure. Keep the prose alive and readable; avoid solemn report voice.}}

{{setvar::AtelierCoT_WorldLogic::- World logic: literary. Check subtext, social truth, consequence, memory, and theme through action. Make meaning emerge from choices, not explanation.}}
